Allowance.</a> Download the Indexation Allowance table for the month when your company sold the asset and then use the figure for the month when the asset was bought. If any improvements were made, work out the effects of inflation in the same way.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You can check whether your valuation of an asset is correct by filling in a <a href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/forms/cg34.pdf\" title=\"Valuation check for capital gains\" rel=\"external\">valuation form (PDF, 200KB)</a> and sending it to your <a href=\"http://search3.openobjects.com/kbroker/hmrc/locator/locator.jsp?type=0\" title=\"Find your Corporation Tax office\" rel=\"external\">Corporation Tax office.</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Example - working out the gain</h2>\n\n<table>\n  <thead>\n    <tr>\n      <th>Step</th>\n      <th>Result</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <td>1. How much your company got for the asset in May 2011</td>\n      <td>£200,000</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>2. Subtract the amount your company bought it for in November 1997 (£120,000)</td>\n      <td>£200,000 - £120,000 = £80,000</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>3. Subtract any fees (expenses on improving the asset in June 2006 were £10,000)</td>\n      <td>£80,000 - £10,000 = £70,000</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>4. Find the inflation factor for the month it was bought in</td>\n      <td>0.474</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>5. Calculate the indexation allowance - multiply the amount it was bought for by the inflation factor</td>\n      <td>£120,000 x 0.474 = £56,880</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>6. Take away the indexation allowance from the profit</td>\n      <td>£70,000 - £56,880 = £13,120</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>7. Find the inflation factor for the expenses</td>\n      <td>0.185</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>8. Calculate the indexation allowance for the expenses</td>\n      <td>£10,000 x 0.185 = £1,850</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>9. Deduct the indexation allowance for the expenses</td>\n      <td>£13,120 - £1,850 = £11,270</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Gain</strong></td>\n      <td><strong>£11,270</strong></td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The Indexation  Allowance means that there’ll be no gain unless the value of an asset  has gone up by more than the inflation rate.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If you personally sell or dispose of assets you’ve taken out of a company, you may have to pay <a href=\"/capital-gains-tax\" title=\"Capital Gains Tax\">Capital Gains Tax</a> if you make a gain.</p>\n</div>\n"},"updated_at":"2012-10-25T09:56:32+00:00","tags":[{"title":"Running a limited company","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/business%2Flimited-company.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes registering, setting up, company accounts and tax returns","type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=business%2Flimited-company","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/business/limited-company"},"parent":{"title":"Businesses and self-employed","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/business.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Information about starting up and running a business in the UK, including help if you're self employed or a sole trader.","type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=business","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/business"},"parent":null}},{"title":"Business tax","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/business%2Fbusiness-tax.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes Corporation Tax, Self Assessment, Capital Gains Tax and VAT","type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=business%2Fbusiness-tax","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/business/business-tax"},"parent":{"title":"Businesses and self-e